<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920220-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>920220-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Finevest Foods Inc.:   Court Approves Statement   On Chapter 11 Proposal</HL><DATE>02/20/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FVF</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Finevest Foods Inc., Greenwich, Conn., said a bankruptcycourt approved its disclosure statements for an amendedChapter 11 reorganization plan.   Under the amended plan, Finevest's bank lending groupreceives a larger share of the reorganized company's votingstock, 22.5%, up from the previous 15%. But as previouslyindicated, Finevest plans to create an intermediate holdingcompany for its dairy operations, which will issue $90million in senior debt to the bank group, and the banks inturn will provide a $10 million revolving line of credit. Inthe amended plan, Finevest will issue the bank group a newseries of common stock convertible into 22.5% of its votingshares.</LP><TEXT>   The plan also stipulates that the amount unsecuredcreditors receive would be determined by a formulasubtracting administrative, priority, and certain mechanics'lien claims from an $11 million fund. The company estimatesthe ultimate amount available to unsecured creditors atbetween $2.5 million and $3.5 million, with an additional$500,000 that may be available under certain circumstances.   A confirmation hearing is scheduled for May 15, slightlymore than a year after the dairy concern's filing forprotection from creditors in U.S. Bankruptcy Court inJacksonville, Fla.</TEXT></DOC>